git clone https://github.com/gowribharadwaj/SFK.git
cd SFK

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Create the local .env (DON’T commit it)
From the repo root, copy .env.example to .env and edit it. Example commands:
    Copy-Item .env.example .env
    notepad .env

HOW TO DO:
1. cd SFK
2. Copy .env.example to a new file named .env
    Copy-Item .env.example .env
    (it creates a new file .env)
3. open the .env file to edit it. for that, run the following command:
    notepad .ev
4. This will open a window like:
    AOAI_ENDPOINT=
    AOAI_API_KEY=
    AOAI_API_VERSION=
    REDIS_CONNECTION_STRING=
    USE_REDIS=
5. Paste your credentials into that file
6. IMPORTANT: Do NOT commit .env
    Git should ignore .env, because .gitignore already contains:
    .env
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

What to paste:

AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT — exact endpoint URL from Azure (must include https:// and trailing slash if the template expects it).

AZURE_OPENAI_KEY — the subscription key they gave you.

AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT — the deployment name (e.g. gpt-4o).

AZURE_OPENAI_API_VERSION — 2024-12-01-preview (or what the template says).

USE_REDIS -> true or false depending on whether they will use Redis.

If using Redis, set REDIS_URL (or REDIS_CONNECTION_STRING depending on repo) to the connection string they were given (use the exact format provider gave; if it requires rediss:// for SSL use that).

IMPORTANT - Security note: .env is in .gitignore — do not check it into GitHub.    

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Create & activate a Python virtual environment
python -m venv .venv
.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1

EXAMPLE - (.venv) PS C:\Users\you\SFK>

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

pip install -r requirements.txt

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Quick config checks (recommended)

Open .env and confirm all variables are present and values look correct.

Confirm the repo’s code uses the same env variable names. (If you followed the delivered structure it will.)

If using Azure OpenAI, confirm:

AZURE_OPENAI_ENDPOINT looks like https://<your-resource>.openai.azure.com/

AZURE_OPENAI_KEY is non-empty

AZURE_OPENAI_DEPLOYMENT matches the deployment name configured in Azure (not necessarily the model name)

AZURE_OPENAI_API_VERSION set as required (e.g. 2024-12-01-preview)

If using Redis, confirm REDIS_URL is reachable from the laptop. If the provider requires SSL, the connection string may start with rediss:// and the redis library should support it.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Run the server
uvicorn src.main:app --reload --port 8000

you should see logs and a line like:
INFO:     Uvicorn running on http://127.0.0.1:8000 (Press CTRL+C to quit)

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

QUICK CHECK-IN

1. Clone repo & open it.

2. Copy .env.example → .env.

3. Paste Azure + Redis credentials into .env.

4. Create & activate .venv.

5. pip install -r requirements.txt

6. uvicorn src.main:app --reload --port 8000

7. Test with curl/Postman:

    curl -X POST "http://localhost:8000/message" -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -d '{"session_id":"alice","message":"What is the width of 6205?"}'


8. Run tests: pytest -q

9. After assessment: delete .env and rotate keys.